1
00:00:01,518 --> 00:00:03,964
<i>- Previously on</i> The Resident...
<i>- Dr. Okafor frightens me.</i>

2
00:00:03,988 --> 00:00:06,905
- I want her to be my right hand.
- My thoughts exactly.

3
00:00:06,940 --> 00:00:09,052
Who are you? <i>Ms. Booth
works for QuoVadis Labs.</i>

4
00:00:09,076 --> 00:00:10,720
It's a cutting-edge
medical device company.

5
00:00:10,744 --> 00:00:13,412
Medical devices are
even bigger than pharma.

6
00:00:13,447 --> 00:00:15,414
Pacemakers, cochlear implants...

7
00:00:15,449 --> 00:00:17,093
<i>The kid was dying. I had to cut.</i>

8
00:00:17,117 --> 00:00:19,418
You don't make the
decision to cut. I decide that.

9
00:00:19,453 --> 00:00:20,564
Tell me exactly what happened.

10
00:00:20,588 --> 00:00:22,765
Who made the first cut...
You or Conrad Hawkins?

11
00:00:22,789 --> 00:00:26,019
<i>- Marshall is our new</i>
<i>chairman of the board.</i>
- It's time to put this hospital

12
00:00:26,043 --> 00:00:28,811
on a firm financial footing.

13
00:00:28,846 --> 00:00:31,096
Stick to what you know,
and leave the business

14
00:00:31,131 --> 00:00:32,564
to the big boys.

15
00:00:32,600 --> 00:00:34,027
<i>You better open your eyes.</i>

16
00:00:34,051 --> 00:00:35,161
He's certainly here
to scorch the earth.

17
00:00:35,185 --> 00:00:36,446
<i>You're a lot more like me</i>

18
00:00:36,470 --> 00:00:37,886
than you realize.

19
00:00:40,590 --> 00:00:41,918
<i>State your name for the record.</i>

20
00:00:41,942 --> 00:00:45,360
Dr. Conrad Hawkins.

21
00:00:45,395 --> 00:00:47,612
You understand that
you're under oath?

22
00:00:47,648 --> 00:00:50,249
I do.

23
00:00:50,284 --> 00:00:52,400
Remember: "yes," "no,"

24
00:00:52,435 --> 00:00:53,786
"I don't recall."

25
00:00:56,940 --> 00:01:00,542
Where were you on the first day
that you encountered my client?

26
00:01:02,112 --> 00:01:03,512
♪ <i>All right, here we go</i> ♪

27
00:01:03,547 --> 00:01:05,563
♪ <i>Hello, stranger</i> ♪

28
00:01:12,423 --> 00:01:14,367
<i>When did the dizziness start?</i>

29
00:01:14,391 --> 00:01:16,791
About 15 minutes ago.

30
00:01:16,827 --> 00:01:18,104
Aw, you're just a
little dehydrated.

31
00:01:18,128 --> 00:01:20,089
I should have you back
out before the encore.

32
00:01:20,113 --> 00:01:21,963
You said volunteers got in free.

33
00:01:21,999 --> 00:01:23,915
And here you are.

34
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:25,934
In the parking lot.

35
00:01:25,969 --> 00:01:27,580
What'd you think... You'd
be onstage with the bands?

36
00:01:27,604 --> 00:01:29,382
I thought I'd me
able to<i> see</i> the bands.

37
00:01:29,406 --> 00:01:30,600
The bathrooms
have a better view.

38
00:01:30,624 --> 00:01:33,608
Then drink your way
to a bathroom break.

39
00:01:36,630 --> 00:01:38,913
Ah, good, we can
use some extra hands.

40
00:01:38,966 --> 00:01:41,382
Sorry, but I am
here for this guy.

41
00:01:41,418 --> 00:01:43,434
Let's go.

42
00:01:43,470 --> 00:01:45,937
One of the other
doctors called in sick.

43
00:01:45,973 --> 00:01:48,140
- So...
- You took their shift.

44
00:01:48,175 --> 00:01:50,570
Just a couple more hours,
and then I'm all yours.

45
00:01:50,594 --> 00:01:52,489
No, that's fine. I'm sure,
uh, after a few beers,

46
00:01:52,513 --> 00:01:54,791
any guy out there will seem
like a good dance partner.

47
00:01:54,815 --> 00:01:56,998
- I'll dance with you.
- See?

48
00:01:57,034 --> 00:01:59,017
Not dehydrated, you won't.

49
00:01:59,053 --> 00:02:01,436
But seriously, if
you guys need help...

50
00:02:01,471 --> 00:02:02,582
Go.

51
00:02:02,606 --> 00:02:04,301
Somebody should
have some fun today.

52
00:02:04,325 --> 00:02:06,275
I'll see you later.

53
00:02:06,310 --> 00:02:08,543
I'll find you.

54
00:02:10,063 --> 00:02:12,614
God, I really wanted to
see Scott Weiland live.

55
00:02:12,666 --> 00:02:15,968
Well, that'll be tough,
since he's dead.

56
00:02:16,003 --> 00:02:17,848
You're thinking of the
guy from Soundgarden.

57
00:02:17,872 --> 00:02:19,520
No, that's Chris Cornell.

58
00:02:19,556 --> 00:02:21,701
You're thinking of the guy
from Stone Temple Pilots,

59
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:23,291
who is Scott Weiland.

60
00:02:23,327 --> 00:02:25,010
They're both dead?

61
00:02:25,045 --> 00:02:26,211
Are you two done?

62
00:02:34,338 --> 00:02:35,832
Oh, my God.

63
00:02:41,895 --> 00:02:43,645
Somebody get help!

64
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:46,698
Nic! Nic!

65
00:02:47,851 --> 00:02:49,891
The exit's this way, come on!

66
00:02:52,989 --> 00:02:54,801
Go, go, go, go!

67
00:02:54,825 --> 00:02:56,525
Nic?

68
00:02:59,380 --> 00:03:01,724
- What happened?
- I found him like this. No pulse.

69
00:03:01,748 --> 00:03:04,182
- I started compressions.
- Switch.

70
00:03:04,217 --> 00:03:05,884
Yeah. I'll get help.

71
00:03:21,118 --> 00:03:23,135
♪ ♪

72
00:03:32,646 --> 00:03:35,580
32-year-old male found down
without a pulse. Now with ROSC.

73
00:03:35,615 --> 00:03:39,367
- Multiple external injuries.
- BP 105/80. Heart rate 110.

74
00:03:39,420 --> 00:03:42,214
- Did he get any fluids?
- Two liters. He needs a pan scan.

75
00:03:42,238 --> 00:03:43,749
- Do we have any idea
what happened?
- Radio said

76
00:03:43,773 --> 00:03:46,173
a couple speakers blew, but
everyone thought it was a bomb.

77
00:03:48,128 --> 00:03:49,271
Blunt abdominal
trauma, hypotensive.

78
00:03:49,295 --> 00:03:51,296
Are ambulances on a level zero?

79
00:03:51,332 --> 00:03:52,892
- Yeah, patients
going all over town.
- Get ready

80
00:03:52,916 --> 00:03:54,048
for a full house, people.

81
00:03:54,083 --> 00:03:55,912
Open-arm fracture
and hemoptysis.

82
00:03:55,936 --> 00:03:58,052
I need another large-bore I.V.

83
00:03:58,105 --> 00:04:00,889
One, two, three.

84
00:04:00,941 --> 00:04:03,308
I heard you need extra hands.

85
00:04:06,063 --> 00:04:07,773
Bleeding's controlled.

86
00:04:07,797 --> 00:04:09,209
All right, it's getting
pretty crazy in here,

87
00:04:09,233 --> 00:04:12,400
but, uh, no more
improv surgeries, okay?

88
00:04:12,453 --> 00:04:13,763
Our gunshot kid
during the blackout...

89
00:04:13,787 --> 00:04:16,037
- He made it, didn't he?
- Yeah, but you barely did.

90
00:04:16,073 --> 00:04:18,256
Bell put me on the spot,

91
00:04:18,292 --> 00:04:20,074
asked me who made the first cut.

92
00:04:22,463 --> 00:04:23,611
What'd you say?

93
00:04:24,665 --> 00:04:25,947
Nothing.

94
00:04:28,869 --> 00:04:30,780
But don't make me
cover for you again, okay?

95
00:04:30,804 --> 00:04:32,504
Thanks.

96
00:04:33,641 --> 00:04:36,274
Dr. Hawkins, they want
you in the VIP room.

97
00:04:36,309 --> 00:04:38,738
Yeah, I'm a little busy.

98
00:04:38,762 --> 00:04:41,002
- Well, someone's got to go.
- Hey, I got it.

99
00:04:45,936 --> 00:04:48,770
I was about to go onstage,

100
00:04:48,805 --> 00:04:50,917
play my set.

101
00:04:50,941 --> 00:04:52,957
That's when I heard that noise.

102
00:04:52,993 --> 00:04:54,754
Is everyone okay?

103
00:04:54,778 --> 00:04:56,306
Let's focus on you
right now, Mr. Barrett.

104
00:04:56,330 --> 00:04:59,531
Looks like you got
stomped on pretty bad.

105
00:04:59,566 --> 00:05:02,116
Actually, I just
tripped backstage.

106
00:05:05,673 --> 00:05:07,288
Is someone in the bathroom?

107
00:05:07,323 --> 00:05:09,190
Hey, Tony.

108
00:05:09,226 --> 00:05:13,011
Doc, this is Tony,
my sober companion.

109
00:05:13,046 --> 00:05:14,496
Tony, this is Doc.

110
00:05:17,017 --> 00:05:19,667
Tony's just making
sure the room's clean.

111
00:05:19,702 --> 00:05:23,355
You'd be surprised what
people leave behind in hotels.

112
00:05:23,390 --> 00:05:25,785
It's a hospital.

113
00:05:25,809 --> 00:05:28,543
Maids leave stuff all the time.

114
00:05:30,213 --> 00:05:31,958
How long have you
been sober, Mr. Barrett?

115
00:05:31,982 --> 00:05:33,648
Almost a year.

116
00:05:33,701 --> 00:05:35,683
Got to get that chip.

117
00:05:37,204 --> 00:05:39,470
It did get ugly, though.

118
00:05:39,505 --> 00:05:42,007
The more records I sold,
the more drugs I took.

119
00:05:42,042 --> 00:05:45,009
I nearly drank myself
to death a few years ago.

120
00:05:45,045 --> 00:05:46,961
Had to quit the tour,

121
00:05:46,997 --> 00:05:49,180
take some time to dry out.

122
00:05:49,216 --> 00:05:52,400
That show today was
supposed to be my big comeback.

123
00:05:55,538 --> 00:05:57,522
You have a
possible tibia fracture.

124
00:05:57,558 --> 00:05:59,840
While we get your X-rays
we'll get you on oxycodone

125
00:05:59,893 --> 00:06:02,343
- for the pain, okay?
- No, no, no, no. No pills.

126
00:06:02,378 --> 00:06:04,824
No booze, nothing.

127
00:06:04,848 --> 00:06:08,349
Only vice I've got
left are these babies.

128
00:06:08,385 --> 00:06:09,701
You want one?

129
00:06:09,737 --> 00:06:11,903
I'm good.

130
00:06:11,938 --> 00:06:14,239
We'll be back.

131
00:06:15,909 --> 00:06:18,927
- Does he seem a little drunk to you?
- Yes.

132
00:06:18,962 --> 00:06:20,882
Add a blood
alcohol test. Tox, too.

133
00:06:20,914 --> 00:06:22,714
Got it.

134
00:06:25,385 --> 00:06:28,169
Mm. So, Julian,
what do you advise

135
00:06:28,205 --> 00:06:31,389
for an abdominal wall
this well-upholstered?

136
00:06:31,425 --> 00:06:32,707
Try these retractors.

137
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:34,876
They're non-slip.
Designed for bariatrics.

138
00:06:37,664 --> 00:06:39,630
I'm glad Prince Abdulraheem

139
00:06:39,666 --> 00:06:41,077
requested you
personally, Dr. Bell.

140
00:06:41,101 --> 00:06:43,284
We miss you down here.

141
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:45,219
Well, thank you, Jessica.

142
00:06:45,272 --> 00:06:47,805
I love the Saudis.
Ideal patients.

143
00:06:47,841 --> 00:06:50,559
They pay same day,
full price, in cash. Mets.

144
00:06:50,611 --> 00:06:52,076
Pick-ups.

145
00:06:52,112 --> 00:06:54,395
We still on for tonight?

146
00:06:54,448 --> 00:06:56,648
Mm-hmm.

147
00:06:56,683 --> 00:06:59,917
Dr. Bell is meeting my
boss tonight, Gordon Page.

148
00:06:59,953 --> 00:07:01,113
He's throwing a
party for the CEOs

149
00:07:01,137 --> 00:07:02,820
who do business with QuoVadis.

150
00:07:02,855 --> 00:07:05,640
Yeah, I'm betting that a guy
who went from med school dropout

151
00:07:05,675 --> 00:07:07,503
to start-up billionaire
in five years

152
00:07:07,527 --> 00:07:09,722
can entertain like a rock star.

153
00:07:09,746 --> 00:07:10,912
His open bar is epic.

154
00:07:10,947 --> 00:07:13,098
He flies a mixologist
in from Miami Beach.

155
00:07:13,133 --> 00:07:16,584
Oh. If you need a
plus-one, I'm free.

156
00:07:20,290 --> 00:07:22,307
The pick.

157
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:35,953
See how we mind
the patellar tendon

158
00:07:35,989 --> 00:07:37,772
as we saw the posterior tibia.

159
00:07:41,327 --> 00:07:43,445
Retractor, please.

160
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:45,041
PCL, right?

161
00:07:45,065 --> 00:07:46,581
That's right.

162
00:07:46,616 --> 00:07:50,118
Oscillating saw's best
to resect damaged areas

163
00:07:50,170 --> 00:07:51,469
of the proximal tibia.

164
00:07:51,504 --> 00:07:53,621
Then we size the implants

165
00:07:53,657 --> 00:07:55,624
and cement the components.

166
00:07:55,659 --> 00:07:57,825
Oh, it's a beautiful
procedure, isn't it?

167
00:07:57,878 --> 00:07:59,978
Go ahead, you try.

168
00:08:00,013 --> 00:08:02,513
Get in there and
do the next cut.

169
00:08:05,068 --> 00:08:07,352
You all right, dear?

170
00:08:07,387 --> 00:08:10,538
♪ <i>Well, I'm tired, so sick,
tired of breakin' down...</i> ♪

171
00:08:14,811 --> 00:08:17,628
♪ <i>When you come around</i> ♪

172
00:08:17,664 --> 00:08:20,464
♪ <i>And crossroads, alleys
and empty streets...</i> ♪

173
00:08:36,366 --> 00:08:38,800
Don't be too hard on yourself.

174
00:08:38,835 --> 00:08:41,147
But time for a gut check.

175
00:08:41,171 --> 00:08:43,131
Not too late to go
into dermatology.

176
00:08:45,374 --> 00:08:47,241
Dr. Bell. Randolph. My man.

177
00:08:47,277 --> 00:08:49,811
- Make an appointment.
- Amazing thing.

178
00:08:49,846 --> 00:08:52,263
I checked the schedule, and
we're both available right now.

179
00:08:52,298 --> 00:08:53,581
I'm on a much-needed break.

180
00:08:53,616 --> 00:08:55,700
Which you'll share with me.

181
00:08:55,735 --> 00:08:58,253
I let you get away
with this why?

182
00:08:58,288 --> 00:08:59,670
Hmm.

183
00:08:59,706 --> 00:09:03,169
I need to establish better
boundaries with staff.

184
00:09:03,193 --> 00:09:05,693
Why, dear man, did you assign me

185
00:09:05,729 --> 00:09:08,612
yet another moist
towelette of a resident?

186
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:11,833
What, Coleman? He graduated
Baylor at the top of his class.

187
00:09:11,868 --> 00:09:14,051
He nearly fainted in my OR.

188
00:09:14,087 --> 00:09:16,588
We're a teaching hospital.
Teach him, he can learn.

189
00:09:19,092 --> 00:09:20,458
Who's this douche?

190
00:09:20,493 --> 00:09:22,722
Head of the hottest new medical
device company in the country.

191
00:09:22,746 --> 00:09:25,430
Also the most eligible
bachelor, I'm told.

192
00:09:25,465 --> 00:09:26,681
Oh, come on, Bell.

193
00:09:26,716 --> 00:09:29,216
We all know you're the
most eligible bachelor.

194
00:09:29,252 --> 00:09:32,520
All our residents are standouts,

195
00:09:32,555 --> 00:09:34,856
or they wouldn't be at Chastain.

196
00:09:34,891 --> 00:09:37,074
I love Atlanta.

197
00:09:37,110 --> 00:09:38,909
The street art, the craft beer.

198
00:09:38,945 --> 00:09:40,912
A rough-but-ready Irishman

199
00:09:40,947 --> 00:09:44,398
in Buckhead I've been
spending a lot of time with.

200
00:09:44,451 --> 00:09:46,595
But have you seen the
surgical suites at Walter Reed?

201
00:09:46,619 --> 00:09:49,587
Mayo and Stanford
keep calling, too.

202
00:09:49,623 --> 00:09:52,051
I-I don't know how
they all get my number.

203
00:09:52,075 --> 00:09:55,610
I may be able to find
you a replacement.

204
00:09:58,849 --> 00:10:00,281
What? What is it?

205
00:10:03,437 --> 00:10:05,386
A piece of bone.

206
00:10:05,422 --> 00:10:08,956
Ah. It's an occupational hazard.

207
00:10:10,944 --> 00:10:12,004
Keep me happy, Randolph.

208
00:10:14,481 --> 00:10:16,431
What's your full name?

209
00:10:16,483 --> 00:10:17,949
Josh Robinson.

210
00:10:17,984 --> 00:10:20,129
Do you remember where you
were when you lost consciousness?

211
00:10:20,153 --> 00:10:21,902
Uh, at a concert in the park.

212
00:10:21,938 --> 00:10:25,306
Reviewing your chart, you've
had quite the interesting life.

213
00:10:25,341 --> 00:10:26,803
How did you get
so many injuries?

214
00:10:26,827 --> 00:10:31,762
Uh, well, this one,
heli-rafting in Queenstown.

215
00:10:31,797 --> 00:10:34,782
Um, mountain biking in Morocco.

216
00:10:34,818 --> 00:10:38,085
Heat stroke, passed
out. And, uh...

217
00:10:38,121 --> 00:10:39,632
Death Drop in
Zambia, two years ago.

218
00:10:39,656 --> 00:10:41,122
Still can't bend it right.

219
00:10:41,157 --> 00:10:43,035
Someone knows how
to use their vacation time.

220
00:10:43,059 --> 00:10:44,704
I'm a professional
adventure guide.

221
00:10:44,728 --> 00:10:46,710
- Seriously?
- Yeah.

222
00:10:46,746 --> 00:10:48,562
I just took a group free diving.

223
00:10:50,066 --> 00:10:51,543
- Wow.
- Oh, nice.

224
00:10:51,567 --> 00:10:53,467
You on any medications?

225
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:56,704
Uh, yeah. It's in my bag.

226
00:10:56,739 --> 00:10:57,889
Oh, there it is.

227
00:10:57,924 --> 00:11:01,276
- Do you mind?
- No.

228
00:11:01,311 --> 00:11:02,655
You have injuries to
mark your experiences.

229
00:11:02,679 --> 00:11:03,995
I get tattoos to mark mine.

230
00:11:05,414 --> 00:11:06,509
I don't see any
prescription drugs.

231
00:11:06,533 --> 00:11:08,983
These are all supplements.

232
00:11:09,036 --> 00:11:10,668
Oh, Pharma. Bad juju.

233
00:11:10,703 --> 00:11:12,231
Josh.

234
00:11:12,255 --> 00:11:15,506
Do not get me
started on Big Pharma.

235
00:11:15,541 --> 00:11:18,576
Milk thistle, kava
kava, omega-3.

236
00:11:18,611 --> 00:11:20,589
Ironic you take all these
supplements to stay healthy

237
00:11:20,613 --> 00:11:23,464
and you end up stampeded
by a bunch of drunk music fans.

238
00:11:23,499 --> 00:11:26,334
Stampede? What stampede?

239
00:11:26,369 --> 00:11:28,681
<i>And that's when you
realized that my client</i>

240
00:11:28,705 --> 00:11:31,589
- passed out before the stampede?
- Yes.

241
00:11:31,624 --> 00:11:34,975
And how many patients did
you treat that day, Dr. Hawkins?

242
00:11:35,011 --> 00:11:37,511
I don't recall.

243
00:11:37,547 --> 00:11:41,365
More than five? More than ten?

244
00:11:43,069 --> 00:11:45,870
I'll tell you. 20.

245
00:11:45,906 --> 00:11:48,989
Chastain strictly adheres
to ACGME guidelines.

246
00:11:49,025 --> 00:11:50,602
How can one resident
possibly provide

247
00:11:50,626 --> 00:11:52,271
the standard of care
to that many patients?

248
00:11:52,295 --> 00:11:53,878
We do it every day.

249
00:11:56,699 --> 00:11:58,377
<i>Disturbing footage today</i>

250
00:11:58,401 --> 00:12:00,028
<i>from the Hotlanta
Music Festival.</i>

251
00:12:00,052 --> 00:12:02,214
Liver and kidneys
have seen better days.

252
00:12:02,238 --> 00:12:03,671
History of Crohn's, too.

253
00:12:03,707 --> 00:12:06,374
So, lots of signs
of the rock star life.

254
00:12:06,409 --> 00:12:07,803
I'm worried the swelling
from his injury could cause

255
00:12:07,827 --> 00:12:09,393
too much pressure in his leg.

256
00:12:09,429 --> 00:12:11,695
Could lead to poor blood
flow and muscle necrosis.

257
00:12:11,731 --> 00:12:13,909
Compartment syndrome. So
if we don't relieve the pressure,

258
00:12:13,933 --> 00:12:15,528
he'll lose the leg.
What's your plan?

259
00:12:15,552 --> 00:12:17,886
Fasciotomy. I had Ortho
come check his pressures.

260
00:12:17,921 --> 00:12:19,804
- Good.
- They're only at 20.

261
00:12:19,839 --> 00:12:21,555
Well, watch it closely.

262
00:12:21,608 --> 00:12:23,419
If it hits 30, they'll need
to operate right away.

263
00:12:23,443 --> 00:12:25,370
Which is why I have
him on the OR's radar.

264
00:12:25,394 --> 00:12:28,713
But the anesthesiologist said
he'd like to have him sober.

265
00:12:28,748 --> 00:12:33,133
Well, his blood alcohol
concentration is .04.

266
00:12:33,169 --> 00:12:34,819
Give him a few hours.

267
00:12:34,854 --> 00:12:37,655
He says that he hasn't
had a drink in a year.

268
00:12:37,690 --> 00:12:40,708
But his serum alcohol
level tells us he did.

269
00:12:40,743 --> 00:12:44,245
Tests don't lie. Alcoholics do.

270
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:47,298
Yeah, maybe sober
companions, too.

271
00:12:52,172 --> 00:12:55,673
How does one man
take all of these?

272
00:12:55,708 --> 00:12:56,852
Those are just the supplements

273
00:12:56,876 --> 00:12:57,937
that our adventure
guide remembers taking.

274
00:12:57,961 --> 00:12:59,426
Kava kava was banned in Europe

275
00:12:59,462 --> 00:13:00,762
for causing liver toxicity.

276
00:13:00,797 --> 00:13:02,441
That might explain
all the bleeding,

277
00:13:02,465 --> 00:13:04,526
- but not why he passed out.
- If I had to guess,

278
00:13:04,550 --> 00:13:06,512
supplements and dehydration
caused an arrhythmia.

279
00:13:06,536 --> 00:13:08,631
- Knocked him out.
- I'm glad you called.

280
00:13:08,655 --> 00:13:10,855
My firm has over 50
years of experience

281
00:13:10,890 --> 00:13:12,357
with neck injuries, right?

282
00:13:12,392 --> 00:13:15,276
You say the ER doctor
didn't even order an MRI?

283
00:13:15,311 --> 00:13:17,695
That's malpractice.

284
00:13:17,730 --> 00:13:20,848
You know, I'm all for patients'
rights, but doctors' jobs

285
00:13:20,884 --> 00:13:23,367
are hard enough without
these vulture lawyers.

286
00:13:23,402 --> 00:13:25,197
And who gets sued
the most? ER doctors.

287
00:13:25,221 --> 00:13:27,216
Patients need to be able to
sue. It's their only recourse

288
00:13:27,240 --> 00:13:29,707
- for medical error.
- It's abused, and it leads

289
00:13:29,742 --> 00:13:31,854
to cover-our-asses
overtreatment and overtesting.

290
00:13:31,878 --> 00:13:33,556
Forcing doctors to
practice defensive medicine.

291
00:13:33,580 --> 00:13:35,647
Well, let's just
focus on our patients

292
00:13:35,682 --> 00:13:37,681
and ignore the vultures.

293
00:13:47,260 --> 00:13:49,677
Thank you.

294
00:13:49,712 --> 00:13:52,864
I understand that you and
Nurse Nevin are in a relationship.

295
00:13:52,899 --> 00:13:55,233
- Correct?
- That's irrelevant.

296
00:13:55,268 --> 00:13:56,912
Do you think working
with your girlfriend

297
00:13:56,936 --> 00:13:59,153
could possibly have
affected your performance?

298
00:13:59,188 --> 00:14:00,905
Objection. Argumentative.

299
00:14:00,940 --> 00:14:04,742
No. Never. There is no better
nurse practitioner than Nic.

300
00:14:04,777 --> 00:14:06,911
Your client was
lucky to have her.

301
00:14:08,114 --> 00:14:09,931
Wouldn't you agree, Josh?

302
00:14:12,452 --> 00:14:14,168
Easy.

303
00:14:14,221 --> 00:14:15,764
Isn't it true

304
00:14:15,788 --> 00:14:17,187
that you have a history

305
00:14:17,223 --> 00:14:21,059
of deviating from protocol?

306
00:14:23,046 --> 00:14:25,512
I know what you're trying to do.

307
00:14:25,548 --> 00:14:27,715
You're suggesting I
put my patient at risk,

308
00:14:27,751 --> 00:14:32,219
but you don't know a
damn thing about medicine.

309
00:14:32,254 --> 00:14:35,139
Let's take five.

310
00:14:39,395 --> 00:14:42,030
- Conrad.
- I know, I messed up.

311
00:14:42,065 --> 00:14:43,275
I don't need to
hear it from you.

312
00:14:43,299 --> 00:14:45,259
This lawsuit could
end your career.

313
00:14:45,285 --> 00:14:47,919
You could even be
found personally liable.

314
00:14:47,954 --> 00:14:49,882
And the hospital
won't stand by you.

315
00:14:49,906 --> 00:14:52,372
Not everyone at
Chastain is on your side.

316
00:14:52,408 --> 00:14:54,959
- But you are?
- Yes.

317
00:14:54,994 --> 00:14:57,378
You have no idea
what this is like for me.

318
00:14:57,413 --> 00:14:59,797
I know exactly
what this is like.

319
00:14:59,832 --> 00:15:01,265
I get sued all the time.

320
00:15:01,301 --> 00:15:02,978
Yeah, you probably
win every single one,

321
00:15:03,002 --> 00:15:04,301
no matter what you say or do.

322
00:15:04,337 --> 00:15:05,636
Oh, don't be naive.

323
00:15:05,672 --> 00:15:07,739
What happened doesn't matter.

324
00:15:07,774 --> 00:15:11,704
A doctor can do everything
right, and still get screwed.

325
00:15:11,728 --> 00:15:14,979
Just control your emotions,

326
00:15:15,014 --> 00:15:18,149
and let the
lawyers do their job.

327
00:15:18,184 --> 00:15:20,951
I have to tell the
truth, no matter what.

328
00:15:20,986 --> 00:15:24,338
Then you'll lose.

329
00:15:26,659 --> 00:15:28,660
Maybe.

330
00:15:37,486 --> 00:15:41,789
This metalhead is lucky
you brought her to me.

331
00:15:43,209 --> 00:15:44,992
That paper-thin portal vein

332
00:15:45,028 --> 00:15:47,628
could easily be ripped
by a mere mortal.

333
00:15:47,663 --> 00:15:50,431
I can do the Pringle Maneuver.

334
00:15:50,466 --> 00:15:52,528
I can do it better.
Observe. Right angle.

335
00:15:52,552 --> 00:15:53,996
Well, I've done it before,

336
00:15:54,020 --> 00:15:55,614
- flawlessly.
- Well, if there's nothing

337
00:15:55,638 --> 00:15:58,940
left for you to learn,
Dr. Okafor, why are you here?

338
00:15:58,975 --> 00:16:01,191
Good question.

339
00:16:01,227 --> 00:16:03,828
Pressure's still dropping.

340
00:16:03,863 --> 00:16:06,125
We must have another
bleeder in there somewhere.

341
00:16:06,149 --> 00:16:08,493
- Give me another right angle.
- She's losing too much blood.

342
00:16:08,517 --> 00:16:10,702
- Let me help.
- Too many cooks.

343
00:16:10,737 --> 00:16:14,122
Can we think about the safety
of the patient and not your ego?

344
00:16:14,157 --> 00:16:17,207
Yeah, in the words of
my colleague Dr. Seuss,

345
00:16:17,243 --> 00:16:20,962
"With this brain in my head
and this blade in my hand,

346
00:16:20,997 --> 00:16:24,882
I shall save every man,
woman and child in the land."

347
00:16:24,917 --> 00:16:27,552
- That is not Dr. Seuss.
- It's an adaptation.

348
00:16:27,587 --> 00:16:30,838
Let me break it down,
Okafor: my house, my rules.

349
00:16:34,343 --> 00:16:35,726
Pressure's coming back up.

350
00:16:35,761 --> 00:16:37,645
Course it is.

351
00:16:37,680 --> 00:16:39,880
Oh, it's so good to be king.

352
00:16:39,915 --> 00:16:43,534
I'm getting sick of the king
treating me like his valet.

353
00:16:45,771 --> 00:16:50,408
I'll tell you what:
you can close.

354
00:16:53,096 --> 00:16:56,748
Your life can
change in a moment.

355
00:16:56,783 --> 00:17:01,419
Levi was born with a
congenital corneal disease.

356
00:17:01,454 --> 00:17:04,055
He'd never seen his mom,

357
00:17:04,090 --> 00:17:06,090
until a synthetic cornea

358
00:17:06,125 --> 00:17:09,510
<i>from QuoVadis made it possible.</i>

359
00:17:09,545 --> 00:17:11,423
<i>Utilizing advanced
nanotechnology,</i>

360
00:17:11,447 --> 00:17:15,433
<i>we provided better bio
integration, quicker healing...</i>

361
00:17:15,468 --> 00:17:17,518
I don't like being summoned.

362
00:17:17,553 --> 00:17:19,070
<i>You see, at QuoVadis,</i>

363
00:17:19,105 --> 00:17:21,689
<i>we measure our success</i>

364
00:17:21,724 --> 00:17:24,192
<i>by how much we improve
the quality of people's lives.</i>

365
00:17:24,227 --> 00:17:26,410
<i>Which is why I'm so passionate</i>

366
00:17:26,445 --> 00:17:28,762
<i>about our latest
breakthrough device:</i>

367
00:17:28,797 --> 00:17:33,151
<i>a safer, a more effective
vagus nerve stimulator.</i>

368
00:17:35,404 --> 00:17:37,783
Remember that rep serving
free lunch with her device demos?

369
00:17:37,807 --> 00:17:39,790
- Mm.
- This is her boss.

370
00:17:39,825 --> 00:17:43,094
He's barely 30. His
company valued at $4 billion.

371
00:17:43,129 --> 00:17:44,462
He's a salesman, Dr. Bell.

372
00:17:44,497 --> 00:17:46,057
The first thing they
sell is themselves.

373
00:17:47,316 --> 00:17:49,399
This talk of his has
over a million hits.

374
00:17:49,435 --> 00:17:50,635
I find it quite moving.

375
00:17:50,670 --> 00:17:52,053
What am I doing here?

376
00:17:52,088 --> 00:17:54,222
Oh, I'm assigning you to Ortho.

377
00:17:54,257 --> 00:17:57,642
Ha. Bell just made a funny.

378
00:17:57,677 --> 00:17:59,638
I-I am not changing
my residency.

379
00:17:59,662 --> 00:18:01,657
Well, no one said you
were. You're just rotating

380
00:18:01,681 --> 00:18:03,292
through a different
surgical specialty.

381
00:18:03,316 --> 00:18:04,660
This is a teaching
hospital, and when we said,

382
00:18:04,684 --> 00:18:05,950
"See One, Do One, Teach One,"

383
00:18:05,985 --> 00:18:09,120
we didn't literally
mean just one.

384
00:18:09,155 --> 00:18:11,122
See mine, do mine, be mine.

385
00:18:11,157 --> 00:18:12,573
Okafor belongs to me.

386
00:18:12,608 --> 00:18:15,142
I belong to no one. I
chose general surgery.

387
00:18:15,178 --> 00:18:17,778
Me, not you.

388
00:18:17,813 --> 00:18:21,466
Well, my bad, Dr. Bell.

389
00:18:21,501 --> 00:18:23,178
I now see the value in
Okafor doing a dance

390
00:18:23,202 --> 00:18:25,002
with our friends in Ortho.

391
00:18:25,037 --> 00:18:28,372
Happy hammering.

392
00:18:43,973 --> 00:18:46,157
Dr. Okafor, lovely to meet you.

393
00:18:46,192 --> 00:18:48,025
You come highly recommended.

394
00:18:48,060 --> 00:18:51,011
What did Dr. Austin really say?

395
00:18:51,047 --> 00:18:53,196
That you're extremely demanding,

396
00:18:53,232 --> 00:18:55,500
and in need of an
attitude adjustment.

397
00:18:55,535 --> 00:18:57,784
Also too talented for Ortho,

398
00:18:57,837 --> 00:19:00,454
which he called
glorified carpentry.

399
00:19:00,489 --> 00:19:04,175
That was rude of
him, but accurate.

400
00:19:07,046 --> 00:19:08,724
You know what's
beautiful about Ortho?

401
00:19:08,748 --> 00:19:11,365
When something
is broken, we fix it.

402
00:19:11,401 --> 00:19:14,151
First up, full hip replacement.

403
00:19:14,186 --> 00:19:17,555
Shall we go and give the
patient the ability to walk again?

404
00:19:22,228 --> 00:19:25,313
Come on, just let
it go. Relax, relax.

405
00:19:25,348 --> 00:19:26,813
LFTs just came in.

406
00:19:26,849 --> 00:19:28,743
Let me guess.
Alcoholic liver disease?

407
00:19:28,767 --> 00:19:30,151
Early stage.

408
00:19:30,186 --> 00:19:31,663
Relax, relax, let it go.

409
00:19:31,687 --> 00:19:33,371
Ingrid, what's going on?

410
00:19:33,406 --> 00:19:35,072
We're having a party.

411
00:19:35,107 --> 00:19:37,224
Are you sure all
he's had are IV fluids?

412
00:19:37,259 --> 00:19:39,238
Oh, I never took my
eyes off him, I swear.

413
00:19:39,262 --> 00:19:41,142
Does this thing
have a gas pedal?

414
00:19:42,582 --> 00:19:45,716
Hey. What'd you slip him?

415
00:19:45,752 --> 00:19:48,002
A drink? Pills?

416
00:19:48,037 --> 00:19:50,788
Let me have a look at that leg.

417
00:19:52,792 --> 00:19:55,709
I'm not drunk. I'm
sober as a judge.

418
00:19:55,744 --> 00:19:57,389
Pressure's too
high. We can't wait.

419
00:19:57,413 --> 00:19:58,907
All right, we need to
get him up to surgery,

420
00:19:58,931 --> 00:20:02,066
or he'll lose his leg. Let's go.

421
00:20:02,101 --> 00:20:06,604
It's his leg, but if he keeps
drinking, it won't matter.

422
00:20:11,093 --> 00:20:12,944
You're up.

423
00:20:12,979 --> 00:20:15,545
You want me to do the impaction?

424
00:20:15,581 --> 00:20:17,815
Mm-hmm.

425
00:20:26,241 --> 00:20:30,310
This hip replacement
needs to be attached firmly.

426
00:20:34,667 --> 00:20:37,885
Think of something
bothering you.

427
00:20:37,920 --> 00:20:41,555
Pissed you got reassigned?
Get out those frustrations.

428
00:20:49,181 --> 00:20:51,126
The news reports
said hundreds of people

429
00:20:51,150 --> 00:20:52,900
were injured at the concert,

430
00:20:52,935 --> 00:20:56,237
most of them seriously, so
why am I only seeing 40 admits?

431
00:20:56,272 --> 00:20:57,649
Where are the brain
injuries, the skull fractures,

432
00:20:57,673 --> 00:20:58,906
the ICU admissions?

433
00:20:58,941 --> 00:21:00,474
My understanding is

434
00:21:00,510 --> 00:21:02,793
the serious cases all
went to Atlanta General.

435
00:21:02,828 --> 00:21:04,940
All of them? We're a
level-1 trauma center.

436
00:21:04,964 --> 00:21:09,116
Why are the EMTs not
sending us the serious cases?

437
00:21:09,151 --> 00:21:12,086
Because Atlanta General
has a new EMT lounge.

438
00:21:12,121 --> 00:21:15,005
They have a 72-inch
TV with sports channels

439
00:21:15,040 --> 00:21:17,675
and a popcorn
machine with real butter.

440
00:21:17,710 --> 00:21:20,261
They have a lounge
just for the EMTs?

441
00:21:20,296 --> 00:21:23,096
I heard Trinity Memorial
is building a better one.

442
00:21:23,131 --> 00:21:25,027
We don't even give
them stale bagels.

443
00:21:25,051 --> 00:21:27,684
It's no wonder the ambulances
are going elsewhere.

444
00:21:27,719 --> 00:21:29,487
Give us the room.

445
00:21:39,014 --> 00:21:41,682
Maybe it's time you
start doing your job

446
00:21:41,717 --> 00:21:45,369
and let someone else cut
open obese Saudi princes.

447
00:21:45,404 --> 00:21:49,340
He requested the
chief of surgery which...

448
00:21:49,375 --> 00:21:51,125
is me.

449
00:21:51,160 --> 00:21:53,544
I've been doing due
diligence for the board.

450
00:21:53,579 --> 00:21:55,996
Our costs are rising

451
00:21:56,031 --> 00:21:58,049
and our profit
margins are shrinking.

452
00:21:58,084 --> 00:22:00,044
Yeah, which is why
I have a meeting

453
00:22:00,068 --> 00:22:01,885
with Gordon Page tonight.

454
00:22:01,921 --> 00:22:04,305
Let me guess,
Chastain agrees to use

455
00:22:04,340 --> 00:22:06,524
only QuoVadis medical devices

456
00:22:06,559 --> 00:22:09,060
and in exchange,
Gordon gives us...

457
00:22:09,095 --> 00:22:12,730
A 20% price cut to
boost our profit margins.

458
00:22:12,765 --> 00:22:15,849
Strong deal for both sides.

459
00:22:15,884 --> 00:22:17,384
I need a better one.

460
00:22:17,420 --> 00:22:20,020
I've already told the board

461
00:22:20,055 --> 00:22:23,407
not to worry because if
you can't land Gordon, I will.

462
00:22:33,435 --> 00:22:35,514
I didn't have time to
go home and change.

463
00:22:35,538 --> 00:22:38,589
Is this too wrinkled?

464
00:22:38,624 --> 00:22:40,758
- No.
- Thanks.

465
00:22:40,793 --> 00:22:42,938
There isn't a full-length
mirror in the ladies room.

466
00:22:42,962 --> 00:22:45,346
I'll get right on that.

467
00:22:45,381 --> 00:22:48,232
This party of
Gordon's is a big deal.

468
00:22:48,267 --> 00:22:50,362
I don't get a lot of face
time with him. He's too busy.

469
00:22:50,386 --> 00:22:52,197
I want to make a
good impression.

470
00:22:52,221 --> 00:22:53,398
Oh, come on, Gordon
can't be tougher

471
00:22:53,422 --> 00:22:55,922
than some of these
doctors at Chastain.

472
00:22:55,958 --> 00:23:00,110
And you've been winning us
over since you walked in that door.

473
00:23:00,145 --> 00:23:01,579
You got this.

474
00:23:01,614 --> 00:23:03,447
I hope so. If I can be the one

475
00:23:03,483 --> 00:23:05,549
to bring Gordon
and Bell together,

476
00:23:05,584 --> 00:23:09,587
I could be looking at a
bonus, which I really need.

477
00:23:09,622 --> 00:23:11,600
I'm helping my parents put
my little sister through college.

478
00:23:11,624 --> 00:23:14,125
You're gonna do great, Julian.

479
00:23:14,160 --> 00:23:16,593
Thanks.

480
00:23:16,628 --> 00:23:18,963
Oh, hey, could
you do me a favor?

481
00:23:18,998 --> 00:23:20,381
Sure.

482
00:23:20,416 --> 00:23:22,933
I heard you're treating
Rhys Barrett in VIP.

483
00:23:22,968 --> 00:23:26,887
If I confirmed that, I
would be violating HIPAA.

484
00:23:26,922 --> 00:23:30,007
Just blink if he's here.

485
00:23:33,762 --> 00:23:35,962
My parents would not
stop playing his albums

486
00:23:35,998 --> 00:23:37,742
when I was a kid;
his songs are basically

487
00:23:37,766 --> 00:23:38,965
the only ones I knew

488
00:23:39,001 --> 00:23:40,411
until I dropped
out of high school.

489
00:23:40,435 --> 00:23:41,819
I'm still not telling you.

490
00:23:41,854 --> 00:23:43,153
Pretty please.

491
00:23:43,188 --> 00:23:44,405
Wait, you dropped out?

492
00:23:44,440 --> 00:23:46,490
I went back. Anyway,
I'll always have

493
00:23:46,526 --> 00:23:47,952
a special place in
my heart for Rhys.

494
00:23:47,976 --> 00:23:50,244
I know he hasn't
toured for years.

495
00:23:50,279 --> 00:23:52,830
Drugs and alcohol, I guess,
which is such a shame,

496
00:23:52,865 --> 00:23:55,815
but I will always be a fan.

497
00:23:55,851 --> 00:23:58,202
I'd love to meet him.

498
00:24:06,378 --> 00:24:08,907
So who's my biggest competition?

499
00:24:08,931 --> 00:24:12,316
Trinity Memorial beats you
on cochlear implants by 15%

500
00:24:12,351 --> 00:24:14,935
but doesn't come close
on caths or aortic valves.

501
00:24:14,970 --> 00:24:16,620
St. John's will make a play.

